k and oral history, and bringing various parts of the African continent into discussion with one another. From Cape Town to Charlottesville, many societies are grappling with historical consciousness and the production of public memory. In particular, how and why societies remember and forget, what should serve as symbols of collective memory, and whether there exists space for multiple memory cultures are questions being vigorously debated once again. These discussions present particular challenges not only to official memory bound to ideological constructions of nationhood but also to the teaching of history and its links to social justice movements. The volume re-centres Africa and African history in memory studies, with each chapter drawing parallels to comparable cases in Africa and the world. An underlying assumption is that what can be learned from the politics of historical memory in Africa will have relevance for contemporary politics globally and for understanding how memories can be mobilised for political ends.  afunded by Schweizerischer Nationalfonds (SNF)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aAfrika. 4aErinnerungskultur. 4aGeschichte. 4aKollektives Gedächtnis. 4aPolitik. 7aHISTORY / Modern / General.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  acollective memory.  ahistorical remembrance.  amemory politics.1 aAndersen, Casper, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharumbira, Ruramisai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFilippi, Natacha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodman, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula